	<h2 class="es-tab-p ">Grammatical cases </h2>
	
	
	<p>
		Russian nouns have special word forms to represent their grammatical function in a sentence. 
		Most often, these word forms are built with help of word endings: words may add or change their ending. 
		These endings are divided into several groups called cases.
	</p>
	<p>
		The Russian language has six cases: nominative, accusative, prepositional, genitive, dative, and instrumental. 
		In each case, words have a form for singular and a form for plural. 
		In this lesson we will talk about the nominative case of Russian nouns. 
	</p>	
<br>
<br>

		
<h2 class="es-tab-p ">Nominative Case</h2>	
<h3 class="es-tab-p-p">Basic info about the nominative case</h3>	
 	
<p>
The nominative case is the basic form of Russian nouns which is usually given in dictionaries.
It functions primarily as the naming case, and is used in the most independant syntactical positions. 
Its main functions are as follows:
</p>
<ul>
	<li>To show the grammatical subject of the sentence. </li>
	<li>As the predicate after the verb быть 'to be' (which is not used in the present tense, as you know).</li>
</ul>
<p>
In our previous lessons, we already used nouns in the nominative case with the above mentioned functions.
</p>

<h3 class="es-tab-p-p">Nominative Singular</h3>

<p>
The nominative case forms are given in dictionaries. 
So, you don't need to change a noun taken from a dictionary or vocabulary list if you are going to use it in the nominative singular.
</p>

<h3 class="es-tab-p-p">Nominative plural </h3>

<p>
In this lesson, we will discuss essential rules to form nominative singular. 
However,  you should keep in mind, that there are many particular cases that do not conform to these rules
</p>

<p>
So, nominative plural endings are -ы/-и for masculine and neuter nouns and -а/-я for neuter nouns. 
These endings are added to the stem of nouns, which is formed by dropping nominative singular endings. 
The endings -и and -я (for neuter nouns) are used if the last consonant of the stem is soft (so, called soft stem). 
</p>
<p>
Formally, we can represent the first rules to build nominative plural from nominative singular: 
</p>
<p class="bold">1. Masculine nouns: </p>
<ul>
	<li>add the ending -ы if they end in a consonant</li>
	<li>add the ending -и, if they end in -ь or -й (i.e. -ь or -й  is replaced by -и)*</li>
</ul>
<p>
In some masculine nouns with a stressed final syllable in the stem, the change from singular to plural is accompanied by a shift of the stress from stem to the ending. This stress shift is usually shown in the dictionary. 
</p>

<p class="bold">2. Feminine nouns:</p>
<ul>
	<li>add the ending -ы to the stem, if they end in -а</li>
	<li>add the ending -и to the stem, if thy end in -я or -ь*</li>
</ul>

<p class="bold">3. Neuter nouns </p>
<ul>
	<li>add the ending -а to the stem, if they end in -о</li>
	<li> add the ending -я to the stem, if thy end in -е or -ё.</li>
</ul>
<p>
In many two-syllable neuter nouns the change from singular to plural is accompanied by a shift of the stress: the syllable that is unstressed in singular becomes stressed in plural. 
</p>
<p>
* -ь and -й are not considered to be endings of nouns, they are part of the stem in the nominative singular. At the same time, they will be dropped in other cases. 
</p>

